<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3342&amp;p=23822#p23822"><![CDATA[
Are you asking so you can find how deep your emulator's pixel buffer needs to be in order to emulate any possible NES program accurately? It is definitely possible to display all ~416 (52*8) colors on screen at once when PPU rendering is disabled (see <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=1209" class="postlink">Full 410-Color NES Palette Demo</a>). Once the pixel is output in the video signal, its color can't be changed, so you can think of your pixel map as the video signal.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Mon Apr 30, 2007 5:38 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
